In 193 B.c. he was driven from Carthage to avoid being surrendered to the Romans, and went to Antiochus of Syria. The plan of campaign which he wished that king to adopt was that he himself should be sent with a small force to ronse Carthage once more against Rome, and to cross over to Italy, while Antiochus advanced thither across Greece. The battle of Magnesia, which took place in 191 B.c., forced Hannibal to leave Syria. He died at Libyssa, in Bithynia, about 182 13.c.

Nepos has plenty of praise for the ability of Hannibal, both as a general and as a statesman. We could wish that he had given more details as to his character. He says nothing, for instance, about his influence over other men, which made him the most wonderful general of a host of mercenaries of differ- ent nations that the world has ever seen.
